he National Magazine Award.</p> <p>She is the author of&nbsp;<a href=\\"http://geni.us/2mZv\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><em>Madness Visible</em></a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\\"http://geni.us/3pXj\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><em>The Quick and the Dead</em></a>,&nbsp;<em><a href=\\"http://geni.us/NL4\\" target=\\"_blank\\">The Place at the End of the World</a>,</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\\"http://geni.us/ghostsdaylight\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><em>Ghosts by Daylight</em></a>&nbsp;which recently won Spears Best Memoir of the Year. She wrote the introduction to the international best seller&nbsp;<em><a href=\\"http://geni.us/1u3Y\\" target=\\"_blank\\">Zlata&rsquo;s Diary: a Child&rsquo;s Life in Sarajevo</a>.</em>&nbsp;Two documentaries have been made about her life and work (<em>Bearing Witness</em> and <em>No Man&rsquo;s Land</em>).  In 2010, she was the President of the Jury of the Prix Bayeux-Calvados  for War. She is now focused on Syria, Egypt, Libya and Yemen and so far  has been inside Syria three times. Janine lives in Paris.</p>", "slug": "janine_di_giovanni", "whotheyare": "Janine di Giovanni reports from war zones around the world.", "whatotherssay": "", "id": 1524, "photo_url": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/82ae75d5ff3028911c9c85015fe0e3dae21c61ec_254x191.jpg"}], "title": "What I saw in the war", "take_action": null, "comments": 17569, "more_resources": null, "hero": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/f795d8100cf916de51cba8309d092446fbd872a1_2880x1620.jpg", "description": "Reporter Janine di Giovanni has been to the worst places on Earth to bring back stories from Bosnia, Sierra Leone and most recently Syria. She tells stories of human moments within large conflicts -- and explores that shocking transition when a familiar city street becomes a bombed-out battleground.", "tags": ["PTSD", "Syria", "TEDx", "global issues", "journalism", "war"], "downloads": {"languages": [{"languageCode": "sq", "endonym": "Shqip", "isRtl": false, "ianaCode": "sq", "languageName": "Alba